<article>

  <p>
    The Sallatha
    <span class="pali" data-pali="sutta" data-en="discourse">Sutta</span>
    (SN 36.6) is often remembered for one image: being struck by a dart, then
    by a second. The discourse itself is doing more than coining a metaphor. It
    compares two patterns of response to
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    — how the uninstructed person becomes fettered by pleasant, painful, and
    neutral feeling, and how the well-instructed disciple meets the same three
    without that binding.
  </p>

  <p>
    The
    <a href="/concepts/second-arrow/">second-arrow page</a>
    tracks the usable distinction in ordinary time. This page stays closer to
    the text: what the Buddha actually contrasts, what follows the second dart
    in the uninstructed cascade, and what "one feeling" means when it is
    clearly known. It is not a demand to feel less, and it is not a
    performance standard for serenity. It asks how feeling is met when it
    arrives — which it does for everyone.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Both Feel the Three</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta opens by refusing a flattering fantasy. The uninstructed person
    experiences pleasant, painful, and neutral feeling. The well-instructed
    noble disciple experiences the same three. Awakening is not a special
    exemption from
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>.
    The difference is not which tones arrive. The difference is what happens
    when they do.
  </p>

  <p>
    That framing matters. A common misreading treats the teaching as if the
    trained mind simply stopped feeling pain. The text says otherwise. Contact
    still delivers tone. Aging, insult, illness, and ordinary friction keep
    arriving. What the discourse tracks is the cascade that often follows
    painful feeling — and whether that cascade is treated as inevitable.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Struck Once, or Twice</h2>

  <p>
    When an uninstructed person is contacted by a painful feeling, the Buddha
    says, he sorrows, grieves, and laments; he weeps, beating his breast, and
    becomes distraught. He feels two feelings — a bodily one and a mental one.
    The image is blunt: as if a person were struck by a dart, and then
    immediately by a second.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "When an uninstructed worldling is contacted by a painful feeling, he
    sorrows, grieves, and laments; he beats his breast and weeps, becoming
    distraught. He feels two feelings — a bodily one and a mental one. …
    When a well-instructed noble disciple is contacted by a painful feeling,
    he does not sorrow, grieve, or lament. … He feels one feeling — a bodily
    one, not a mental one."
    <cite>— SN 36.6, Sallatha Sutta (adapted)</cite>
  </blockquote>

  <p>
    The instructed disciple feels the first dart and does not invite the
    second. Notes, not conclusions: the sutta's "bodily" / "mental" contrast
    is a teaching distinction about reaction, not a map of which pains count
    as real. A harsh word and a medical report can both be first strikes. The
    leverage the text names is whether sorrowing and lamenting are added on
    top — further contact with pain, optional in a way the first dart often is
    not. Optional does not mean easy. It means trainable.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>Resistance, Anusaya, and the Wrong Escape</h2>

  <p>
    The sutta does not stop at the image of two darts. It follows the
    uninstructed pattern further. Touched by painful feeling, the person
    resists it. Under that resistance, an underlying tendency —
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anusaya" data-en="underlying tendency">anusaya</span>
    — of aversion toward painful feeling settles in. Then, under the impact of
    the pain, he proceeds to enjoy sensual happiness. Why? Because he does not
    know another escape from painful feeling except sensual pleasure.
  </p>

  <p>
    That sequence is the discourse's distinctive claim, beyond the popular
    two-arrow summary. Painful feeling is resisted; aversion digs a groove;
    pleasure is seized as the only exit. The first event was unpleasant
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>.
    The rest is a mind trying to get away from
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    without knowing it according to arising and ending.
  </p>

  <p>
    The text adds a further cost. Not knowing feelings — their gratification,
    danger, and escape — an underlying tendency to ignorance regarding
    neutral feeling also takes root. And when pleasant feeling is chased
    without clear knowing, an
    <span class="pali" data-pali="anusaya" data-en="underlying tendency">anusaya</span>
    of lust for pleasant feeling is fed as well. Pleasant, painful, and
    neutral tones are then felt as one who is fettered by them. The problem
    is not that feeling occurs. The problem is being bound by each tone as it
    appears.
  </p>

  <hr>

  <h2>One Feeling, Clearly Known</h2>

  <p>
    The instructed pattern is the reverse. Painful feeling arises. There
    is no sorrowing and lamenting cascade. Resistance does not dig in, so the
    underlying tendency of aversion is not reinforced. Sensual pleasure is not
    seized as the only exit. Feelings are known according to their arising and
    ending — their allure, their danger, and the escape that is not just another
    craving. Pleasant, painful, or neutral: they are felt as one who is not
    fettered by them.
  </p>

  <p>
    In
    <a href="/suttas/satipatthana/"><span class="pali" data-pali="satipaṭṭhāna" data-en="foundations of mindfulness">satipaṭṭhāna</span></a>
    terms, that knowing is already practice language: unpleasant
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    as unpleasant
    <span class="pali" data-pali="vedanā" data-en="feeling-tone">vedanā</span>
    — ardent, clearly knowing, mindful — before the mind has fully recruited it
    into grievance or rescue. The
    <a href="/concepts/vedana/">vedanā page</a>
    names that seam more closely. The
    <a href="/concepts/second-arrow/">second-arrow page</a>
    stays with catching the turn in ordinary scenes — including how the
    teaching is misused as numbness, bargain, or a ban on wise response. This
    sutta is their source: the structure of instructed versus uninstructed
    response, and the tendencies that grow when feeling is met in the dark.
  </p>

  <p>
    Nothing here is final. The discourse does not ask anyone to become a person
    who never elaborates. It shows a trainable difference: same three feelings,
    different binding. Painful feeling will keep arriving. The distraught
    second strike — and the wrong escape that follows it — need not.
  </p>

</article>
